<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/opinion <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/opinion" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 10 日星期四 01:22:32 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The Blue State Migrant Crisis]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>纽约市和马萨诸塞州呼吁失败的特区提供移民帮助和工作许可<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140212648158990"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140212648158990"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 6:49（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-blue-state-migrant-mess-721d823b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832996?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 9 日，纽约市市长埃里克·亚当斯 (Eric Adams) 谈论寻求庇护者及其对纽约市的影响。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：迈克尔·布罗克斯坦/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如今媒体大多忽视了移民危机，但不要告诉纽约市市长埃里克·亚当斯一切已经结束。当该市预计本月将接收从墨西哥边境运来的第 10 万名移民时，他大声喊叫。</p><p>市长周三举行新闻发布会，描述了移民对该市预算的压力，并要求华盛顿提供更多资金。纽约在 2023 财年为移民提供庇护服务花费了 14.5 亿美元，并于 6 月批准了 29 亿美元为 2024 年新移民提供资金。但两个月后，它已经知道这还不够。</p><p> “我们的新估计表明，我们在本财年应对这场危机的支出接近 50 亿美元，”亚当斯先生说。这超过了该市卫生、公园和消防部门的总成本。</p><p>该市的初步成本预测是根据去年至今年春季的移民到达率进行的。这错过了数十万移民，他们将抵达时间推迟到第 42 条规定结束后，联邦政府于 5 月暂停了这项边境执法政策。成千上万的人正在前往纽约。</p><p>费用增长的最大来源是仍在该市庇护所中的寻求庇护者比例——超过 57,000 人。 “我们平均每晚花费 383 美元来提供住房、食物、医疗保健和社会服务，”亚当斯先生谈到每个家庭的成本时说道。也就是说，收容所内的人员每天需要花费 980 万美元。</p><p>大部分责任都归咎于拜登政府，如果他们申请庇护，他们就会放手让数十万移民进入美国。罪魁祸首还应归咎于1996年的一项联邦法律，该法律规定寻求庇护者必须有五个月的等待期才能申请工作许可证，这使得他们在抵达后没有任何有效的选择。</p><p>据该市称，能够靠低薪、课外工作生活的单身成年人可以快速通过庇护所系统。但在有孩子的家庭中，由于无法找到工作，超过 80% 的家庭在第一个月之后就住在庇护所里。</p><p>这导致了像上周在曼哈顿中城中央车站附近的罗斯福酒店临时避难所发生的奇观。酒店已满员，数百名移民日日夜夜睡在商业区中心的人行道上。该市正在讨论在公园或东河兰德尔斯岛建立新的避难所，但这些避难所价格昂贵，而且会占用年轻人宝贵的娱乐空间。</p><p> “我直接从与我交谈过的寻求庇护者那里听到了这样的说法：他们想要工作，”市长亚当斯周三表示。 “他们没有工作许可，所以我们必须提供庇护所。”国会和拜登政府可能会修改法律，但在移民问题上华盛顿却表现不佳。</p><p>马萨诸塞州州长莫拉·希利本周也因移民涌入人数激增而宣布进入紧急状态。她谴责“联邦不作为危机”，并要求加快工作授权。</p><p>民主党在特朗普执政期间声称自己是“庇护”城市和州的政治噱头不再有趣了。他们正在了解德克萨斯州和佛罗里达州的感受。如果他们想得到缓解，他们就必须开始对拜登政府施加更大的压力，诚实地对待其移民失败。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5142C94E-13A6-499A-B6D4-6A6C8A9266FE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-blue-state-migrant-mess-721d823b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：美国经常被描述为“移民国家”，但随着拜登的开放河流或特朗普的另一堵墙，美国卓越地位的时钟可能会停止，因为非法移民玷污了获得公民身份的合法途径。图片：法新社/盖蒂图片社/祖玛出版社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 22:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-blue-state-migrant-mess-721d823b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-blue-state-migrant-mess-721d823b<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Punishing Banks for Regulatory Failure]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>监管机构希望对中型银行实施新的资本规定。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128412662964990"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128412662964990"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 6:39 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/punishing-banks-for-regulatory-failure-svb-fed-capital-requirements-52e361a5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832943?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>硅谷银行倒闭的原因是利率上升和监管机构的失误，而不是资本短缺。然而，监管机构正在利用春季银行业恐慌来证明繁琐的新资本规则的合理性，这些规则可能会使金融体系更加脆弱。</p><p>美联储、联邦存款保险公司和货币监理署最近提出了一项长达 1,087 页的规则，将中型和大型银行的资本要求平均提高 16%。强大的资本水平有助于保护纳税人，当它们清晰简单时我们会青睐它们。但正如美联储主席杰罗姆·鲍威尔在一份声明中指出的那样，目前提高资本要求的潜在成本可能超过收益。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>拟议标准将涵盖大约 30 家资产超过 1000 亿美元的银行，这实际上使国会 2018 年的两党银行业改革无效，该改革将中型银行从“大而不能倒”的规则中解放出来。这就是该规则的明确政治意图。 Flagstar 银行必须遵守与摩根大通相同的资本要求，尽管其规模只有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JPM" class="company-name">摩根</a>大通的 1/25。</p><p>银行必须持有更多资本来应对监管处罚、诉讼和网络攻击等“运营”风险。资本要求将基于银行规模和过去因运营问题造成的损失。因此，监管机构可以对银行进行两次催款——首先是罚款，然后是要求银行持有更多资本以应对未来的处罚。</p><p>该提案还将对交易风险提出更高的资本要求，这将在银行间标准化。如果银行从事监管机构认为风险较高的活动，则必须持有更多资本。这听起来很明智。</p><p>但正如鲍威尔在一份声明中解释的那样，这可能会刺激大型银行减少做市活动，“威胁到关键市场流动性的下降，以及其中一些活动进入影子银行领域。”毫无疑问，监管机构随后将尝试扩大对冲基金、私募股权和其他非银行机构的监管范围，以填补市场缺口，就像奥巴马时期所做的那样。</p><p>该规则的交易风险加权制度也会鼓励羊群行为并增加监管套利。这就是 2008 年金融恐慌之前发生的情况，当时银行大量购买抵押贷款支持证券，因为监管机构认为这些证券没有风险。你知道结果如何。</p><p>银行已经必须遵守众多重叠的资本制度，而美联储的提议将在经济存在巨大不确定性的时候增加另一个资本制度。穆迪本周下调了 10 家中型银行的信用评级，并对 6 家银行进行了审查，银行债券遭受重创。如果筹集新资本成本过高，更严格的资本规则将导致银行减少“风险加权资产”和贷款。</p><p>另一个原因是，这些规则转移了银行经理对实际风险管理的注意力，硅谷银行似乎就发生了这种情况。美联储监管副主席迈克尔·巴尔 (Michael Barr) 关于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SIVBQ" class="company-name">SVB</a>的报告</p>指出银行经理和监管者花费了“相当大的努力来理解这些规则以及它们何时适用。”<p></p><p>然而，根据拟议的规则，倒闭的三家银行都不会被要求持有更多资本。虽然交易的资本费用将对投资银行造成最严重的打击，但很难准确预测这一复杂的规则将如何影响信贷和市场。</p><p>为了强调出现意外后果的可能性，共和党 FDIC 董事会成员乔纳森·麦克南 (Jonathan McKernan) 举了一个例子，一家银行因消费者合规问题而遭受巨额监管处罚。因此，该银行对某些住宅房地产和零售业务的资本要求将降低。</p><p>可以肯定的是，更高的合规性和资本成本将给中型银行带来不成比例的负担。这将降低他们与巨头的竞争力，并增加他们通过合并做大的动力。但只要财政部长，呃，参议员伊丽莎白·沃伦（Elizabeth Warren）在监视着他们，美联储监管机构就不会允许他们合并。</p><p>监管机构越是试图惩罚大银行，就越是惩罚其竞争对手，而美国人最终也会以某种方式为错误的监管付出代价。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7F713F19-EC78-404A-89C8-6326F4FD2ADD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fpunishing-banks-for-regulatory-failure-svb-fed-capital-requirements-52e361a5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：似乎特朗普和拜登还不够，美国两位最著名的首席执行官实际上可能会一决高下。图片：法新社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 22:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/punishing-banks-for-regulatory-failure-svb-fed-capital-requirements-52e361a5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/punishing-banks-for-regulatory-failure-svb-fed-capital-requirements-52e361a5<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>资本要求</category><category>银行监管</category><category>中型银行</category><category>SVB</category><category>太大而不能失败</category><category>银行业</category><category>商业银行</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>美国联邦储备</category><category>货币监理署</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>银行业</category><category>商业银行</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Pennsylvania’s Big Government-Union Payback]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>州长乔什·夏皮罗签署了为他的主要竞选贡献者大幅加薪的协议。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590138533525047698"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590138533525047698"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 6:38 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pennsylvanias-big-government-union-payback-647abbae"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832936?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">宾夕法尼亚州州长乔什·夏皮罗</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马特·洛克/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>工会一直在从民主党州长那里获得大幅加薪，最新的结果是在宾夕法尼亚州。周一，美国州、县和市政雇员联合会 (Afscme) 签署了一份新合同，其中包括在四年内加薪 20.25%。</p><p>工会指出，新合同“包括将员工医疗保健缴款增加 0.5%”，但“雇主将增加 28% 的缴款”。试着从你的老板那里得到这个。该合同还包括“增加膳食津贴、扩大假期回购、改进加班政策、改进健康和安全措施等等。”</p><p>这是 Afscme 对州长乔什·夏皮罗 2022 年竞选活动投资 126 万美元的丰厚回报。 2023-2024 年，比之前工会合同增加的金额将使宾夕法尼亚州纳税人损失 8370 万美元。经过四年的提高，国家预算将不得不额外承担 7.24 亿美元的费用。这还不包括基于工资的较大养老金支付的长期成本。</p><p>这就是公职人员工会坐在谈判桌两边时的运作方式。其他账单也将到期：服务业雇员国际工会为夏皮罗先生的竞选活动捐款 150 万美元。据宾夕法尼亚州国务院称，宾夕法尼亚州教育协会和国家教育协会捐款 120 万美元。他们会得到什么？</p><p>根据英联邦基金会追踪的数字，自 2007 年以来，宾夕法尼亚州政府工会通过其政治行动委员会在政治上花费了 1.9 亿美元，并且 2021-2022 年周期打破了记录。在 2021-2022 年周期中，公共工会 PAC 向全州公职候选人提供的捐款中 99.6% 都流向了民主党。</p><p>自最高法院 2018 年<em>Janus</em>裁决要求工人选择加入会员以来，宾夕法尼亚州的工会已经失去了数千名成员。但只要他们的现金有助于民主党当选，他们就会继续编写自己的集体谈判协议条款。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 22:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pennsylvanias-big-government-union-payback-647abbae</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pennsylvanias-big-government-union-payback-647abbae<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>乔什·夏皮罗</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Shame Beijing Into Nuclear-Arms Talks]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>静悄悄的外交是行不通的。是时候召集全球舆论法庭了。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140411477213490"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140411477213490"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">扎卡里·凯克</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 5:56 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/shame-beijing-into-nuclear-arms-talks-weapons-war-nato-nuclear-arsenal-missiles-8ceb0368"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832729?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">米哈伊尔·戈尔巴乔夫和罗纳德·里根于 1987 年签署了《中导条约》。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：str old/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在一系列成功的核试验之后，苏联于 1958 年 3 月 31 日宣布单方面暂停未来的试验。它敦促美国效仿。华盛顿立即明白，莫斯科的目标是影响全球公众舆论，反对美国国务卿约翰·杜勒斯敦促艾森豪威尔总统以暂停核试验作为反击。未来测试中的任何技术收益都不值得以美国的国际地位为代价。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>美国在应对中国不断扩大的核武库时应该牢记这一教训。多年来，华盛顿一直试图通过静悄悄的外交手段说服北京加入核军控讨论。战略耐心已经失效。现在是开始公开谈判并向中国领导人施压的时候了，要求他们坐到谈判桌前，否则就会因日益激烈的军备竞赛而受到正确的指责。</p><p>在整个核时代，公共关系一直是军备控制和防扩散的一部分。杜鲁门政府提议取缔原子武器并将所有核技术置于国际控制之下。艾森豪威尔政府的原子和平计划同样面向全球受众。</p><p> 1987 年《中程核力量条约》的前奏也是由苏联和美国试图塑造公众舆论（尤其是在欧洲）的竞争决定的。莫斯科部署了能够到达整个欧洲的高精度战区弹道导弹，同时还进行了宣传活动，旨在使欧洲公众舆论反对北大西洋公约组织反部署类似导弹的努力。苏联最终希望通过让美国怀疑华盛顿的信誉来使美国和欧洲脱钩。</p><p>北约采取了双轨应对措施。该联盟批准了在欧洲各国部署美国战区弹道导弹和巡航导弹的计划。这让莫斯科感到害怕，因为导弹可以在几分钟内到达苏联领导层。第二条轨道是旨在强调北约和平意图的外交。在所谓的“零选项”中，美国提出，如果莫斯科取消其现有的中程核力量部署，美国将取消其中程核力量部署。不出所料，苏联拒绝了，但这一策略为在欧洲部署新型美国导弹提供了外交空间。一旦美国的导弹到位，莫斯科就同意零选择，几十年来一整类核武器都被消除了。</p><p>如今，中国正在以零透明度的能力或意图建设核武库。北京的核扩张伴随着越来越多的全球核危险以及军备控制协议的迅速瓦解。</p><p>美国应尽可能与盟友和伙伴合作，制定军控建议，并通过公开演讲和国际论坛不断施压。北京不太可能接受任何提案的具体条款，但推动这些条款将迫使中国领导人进行谈判，否则将在全球舆论场上受到指责。</p><p>有几个潜在的建议。其一，中国的核扩张以钚后处理为中心，钚是核弹头的核心。北京已表示这些后处理设施将专门用于民用目的，但在2017年，它不再像其他国家那样自愿披露其钚库存。全球暂停钚后处理，甚至国际原子能机构对这些设施进行严格监控，都将缓解各方的担忧。</p><p>另一种可能性：新的共轨卫星可用于摧毁太空中的其他卫星。美国可能要求限制在其他国家军事卫星附近部署共轨卫星，以防止太空珍珠港事件的风险。华盛顿及其盟友可以提议禁止在陆基洲际弹道导弹上安装许多弹头，或者禁止混合使用核导弹和常规导弹。</p><p>中国的核扩张使得对话和谈判势在必行。静悄悄的外交是行不通的。细节可以商定，但华盛顿必须加大对北京的公众压力。</p><p><em>凯克先生是前美国众议院外交事务委员会工作人员，也是《原子之友：美国如何应对核武器盟友》一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EA264804-D64D-4A44-A204-31F6D29E7A04&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fshame-beijing-into-nuclear-arms-talks-weapons-war-nato-nuclear-arsenal-missiles-8ceb0368&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：俄罗斯、中国和伊朗现在结成联盟，其明确目标是取代美国及其自由价值观。乌克兰是他们的主要活跃战场 (11/02/22)。图片：路透社/法新社/美联社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/shame-beijing-into-nuclear-arms-talks-weapons-war-nato-nuclear-arsenal-missiles-8ceb0368</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/shame-beijing-into-nuclear-arms-talks-weapons-war-nato-nuclear-arsenal-missiles-8ceb0368<category>苏联</category><category>中国</category><category>武器</category><category>战争</category><category>军备竞赛</category><category>原子武器</category><category>条约</category><category>北约</category><category>导弹</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>核武器计划</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>武器计划</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>核武器计划</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>武器计划</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Trump Plays Hamlet Ahead of the Republican Primary Debate]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>他会出现吗？他很腼腆，而且有理由不这样做，但我敢打赌他会这样做。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140230757419588"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590140230757419588"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/karl-rove" itemprop="url" rel="author">卡尔·罗夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 5:56 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-plays-hamlet-ahead-of-the-debate-election-2024-race-gop-candidate-campaign-369ff2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832579?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 8 日，唐纳德·特朗普在新罕布什尔州温德姆举行的竞选集会上发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：约瑟夫·普雷齐奥索/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>争论，还是不争论，这是一个问题。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普（Donald Trump）</a>像丹麦王子一样在问，“拒绝出席 8 月 23 日在密尔沃基举行的共和党总统初选辩论，还是出席“遭受暴行的命运之箭，是否是一种更高尚的心态”？拿起武器对抗纷繁的麻烦/并通过反对结束它们。”</p><p>在上周六阿拉巴马州共和党筹款活动上，特朗普似乎倾向于跳过密尔沃基。在向观众保证“我喜欢辩论”的同时，他补充道：“但你知道，有时你不想成为一个傻瓜。你需要一位聪明的总统”，这意味着回避这一事件是明智之举。他声称，毕竟共和党初选“已经结束，没有人有机会”。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>关于特朗普为什么不参加辩论会更好，有合理的论据。首先，他遥遥领先（根据 RealClearPolitics 的数据为 38 分）。前往密尔沃基让他的竞争对手有机会在全国共和党选民电视观众面前殴打他。为什么要冒着他所推动的不可避免的光环的风险呢？</p><p>作为 2024 年总统大戏的核心人物，特朗普比任何其他共和党或民主党候选人都更受关注。为什么要通过与其他共和党候选人争论来让他们有更多的曝光度？他们需要核心小组成员和初选选民来更好地了解他们。特朗普先生的问题恰恰相反。他面临着暴露过度的风险。</p><p>然后还有更大的法律麻烦的幽灵。一旦他开始说话，他就很容易失控。过度的言语可能会为检方在即将到来的审判中提供更多素材。</p><p>另一方面，特朗普未能露面可能会受到不好的对待。这可能看起来像是软弱的表现（他不愿意为自己辩护）或过度自信（他认为选民是理所当然的）。选民还可能将其视为对福克斯新闻的小小冷落，他将福克斯新闻的高管描述为“一群憎恨全球主义绿诺人的 MAGA”，他们“协助和教唆毁灭美国”。 （我是福克斯新闻撰稿人。）</p><p>如果特朗普缺席，他的对手将更容易将话题从前总统的不满和捏造转向共和党真正关心的问题。有很多共和党选民仍在犹豫不决。尽管《纽约时报》/锡耶纳 7 月 27 日的民意调查显示，现在有 54% 的共和党人支持特朗普，但只有 52% 的支持者表示他们坚定支持——这相当于共和党选民的大约 28%。这比任何其他候选人都多，但还算不上多数。</p><p>如果前总统不在那里将辩论拖回他声称 2020 年选举被窃取的说法（他未能在法庭上证明这一点），那么仍在关注这一领域的初选选民更有可能看到他们更喜欢的人，而不是前总统。相反，他们会看到年轻领导人的观点，不受多重起诉，认为他们可以击败拜登总统，应对美国的挑战，并连任两届。</p><p>在特朗普缺席的情况下，他的共和党竞争对手可能会更加大胆地发起更加严厉和具体的攻击，从而更加有效。这位被三次起诉的前总统将错过反击的机会，而在政治上，反击往往比第一次打击更有效。他很擅长。但如果他反击《Truth Social》，电视上的第一波热播和他在社交媒体上的回应之间的延迟将对他不利。如果他决定擅离职守，就更容易贬低和解雇他。</p><p>除了特朗普本人之外，没有人会全力捍卫他在机密文件或 1 月 6 日起诉书中的立场，这可能会导致他的脆弱性加剧。 8 月 3 日的路透社/益普索民意调查应该会给特朗普团队敲响警钟。调查发现，如果特朗普“被陪审团判定犯有重罪” <a href="https://www.ipsos.com/en-us/reutersipsos-survey-despite-indictments-trump-leads-primary-field-desantis-loses-support" target="_blank" class="icon none">，45% 的共和党人</a>不会投票给他。只有35%的人会投票给他，而20%的人尚未决定。在这场辩论中，共和党认为更具吸引力的候选人可能会在这些观点上反对特朗普。如果他错过了密尔沃基，他就会放弃向越来越多支持他但对他持怀疑态度的共和党人强化自己观点的重要机会。</p><p>那么特朗普先生会做出什么决定呢？特朗普暗示他可能不会参加辩论，这可能是他突然加入的计划的一部分，旨在震惊公众并抢了对手的风头。或者他和他的团队可能已经坚定地认为他失去的比得到的更多。</p><p>如果我是一个赌徒，我会说特朗普先生会出现。他必须成为关注的焦点。但现在没有人知道，可能包括特朗普先生。他可能会在最后一刻做出决定。</p><p><em>罗夫先生帮助组织了政治行动委员会“美国十字路口”，并且是《威廉·麦金利的胜利》（Simon &amp; Schuster，2015 年）一书的作者。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7F713F19-EC78-404A-89C8-6326F4FD2ADD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftrump-plays-hamlet-ahead-of-the-debate-election-2024-race-gop-candidate-campaign-369ff2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：似乎特朗普和拜登还不够，美国两位最著名的首席执行官实际上可能会一决高下。图片：法新社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-plays-hamlet-ahead-of-the-debate-election-2024-race-gop-candidate-campaign-369ff2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-plays-hamlet-ahead-of-the-debate-election-2024-race-gop-candidate-campaign-369ff2<author><![CDATA[Karl Rove]]></author><category>选举</category><category>2024年</category><category>辩论</category><category>种族</category><category>候选人</category><category>总统</category><category>基本的</category><category>民意调查</category><category>共和党</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[My ‘Sweater Theory’ in Practice]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> GK Chesterton 和 CS Lewis 都比我先想到了这个想法。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12099543776899034024404590070011308361680"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12099543776899034024404590070011308361680"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">迈克·克里根</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 5:55 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/my-sweater-theory-in-practice-lewis-chesterton-mere-christianity-339337c4"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832427?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Getty Images/iStockphoto</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>我在法学院上的一堂课讨论了有效市场假说，该假说认为资产的当前股价反映了所有可用信息。在耐心聆听学生对假设的各种形式的讨论后，我们的客座讲师发表了令人难忘的台词。</p><p>他是一家上市公司的首席财务官，有德国口音。他干巴巴地说，他很欣赏年轻法律头脑之间的交流，但在从事了几十年的金融工作之后，对他来说，这无异于说：“我们知道这在实践中是有效的，现在让我们看看它在理论上是如何成立的。”他成为我评选的最有趣的德国经济学家的领跑者。</p><p>随着年龄的增长，我意识到讨论假设的教授是正确的。当值得信赖的权威证实了你长期实践的良好行为背后的理论时，这是有教育意义的，也是令人快乐的。</p><p>近年来，这种情况在我身上发生过两次，一次是作为一名试图抚养好孩子的父亲，一次是作为一名试图进入天堂的基督徒。当我的任何一个公认幸运的孩子表达“如果只有X，一切都会完美”的观点时，他们总是会面对他们父亲的“毛衣理论”生活。</p><p>毛衣理论提醒我们，生命是一个要么全有要么全无的命题，是一份无价的礼物，没有“如果”。就像拉动毛衣的松线一样，看似无害的努力可能会导致套头衫完全散开，让事情变得更糟，而不是稍微好一点。</p><p>想象一下，当我得知 GK 切斯特顿 (GK Chesterton) 的辩护杰作《正统》中警告如下内容时，我会多么高兴：“不要让骆驼摆脱驼峰的负担；不要把骆驼从驼峰的负担中解放出来；你可能会让他不再是一头骆驼。”我的毛衣理论被简洁地阐述了。</p><p>后来我接受了理论，并在我自己的精神之旅中支持实践。当我知道我应该做的好事，但由于我的弱点，我不想这样做时，“假装直到成功”是我经常利用的动力。令人欣慰的是，在我出生之前，CS Lewis 就已经为这一哲学提供了基础。</p><p>刘易斯在《纯粹的基督教》一书中建议：“不要浪费时间去关心你是否‘爱’你的邻居；就像你所做的那样。 。 。 。当你表现得好像你爱一个人时，你很快就会爱上他。”多么有力的证实：不仅假装的时间很短，而且制作的过程可能会带我一路通往天堂。</p><p>当合理的理论在实践中得到证实时，这是令人兴奋的。当合理的实践在理论上成立时，这同样令人惊奇。</p><p> <em>Kerrigan 先生是北卡罗来纳州夏洛特市的一名律师</em></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F39EC653-A48E-4FB7-AF6D-1F040C95B008&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmy-sweater-theory-in-practice-lewis-chesterton-mere-christianity-339337c4&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊社论报告：Kim Strassel、Kyle Peterson、Kate Bachelder 和 Dan Henninger 的本周最佳和最差图片：路透社/美联社综合报道：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/my-sweater-theory-in-practice-lewis-chesterton-mere-christianity-339337c4</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/my-sweater-theory-in-practice-lewis-chesterton-mere-christianity-339337c4<category>纯粹的基督教</category><category>宗教</category><category>理论</category><category>实践</category><category>天主教信仰</category><category>法学院</category><category>经济学</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Musk vs. Zuckerberg Cage Fight]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>似乎特朗普和拜登还不够，美国两位最著名的首席执行官实际上可能会一决高下。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138713096049200"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138713096049200"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/daniel-henninger"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI552_hennin_AM_20180807121334.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/daniel-henninger" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹尼尔·亨宁格</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 5:55 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-musk-vs-zuck-cage-fight-tech-business-media-ceo-fight-ufc-meta-facebook-twitter-x-11853966"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7F713F19-EC78-404A-89C8-6326F4FD2ADD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-musk-vs-zuck-cage-fight-tech-business-media-ceo-fight-ufc-meta-facebook-twitter-x-11853966&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：似乎特朗普和拜登还不够，美国两位最著名的首席执行官实际上可能会一决高下。图片：法新社/盖蒂图片社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div><p>似乎<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">乔·拜登</a>之间重赛的前景还不够，我们现在有可能在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">马克·扎克伯格</a>之间进行一场真正的笼斗。一定有一张报名表可以参与美国的逐底竞争。</p><p>最近有多少次你听到人们说“优雅”，意思是他们所目睹的事情恰恰相反？我们渴望政客和公众人物变得更好，但我们却变得越来越糟。</p><p>不受欢迎的拜登与特朗普重赛似乎是不可避免的，因为民主党和共和党的初选选民似乎都陷入了悬崖边的游行。毫无疑问，在你们的政治出身成为现实之前，牵手的那一刻，会有一场塞尔玛和路易斯的肾上腺素激增。</p><p>在马斯克表示他可能需要对颈部或上背部进行手术后，马斯克与扎克伯格的笼式比赛似乎被搁置。尽管如此，你还是必须清醒地认识到，他们自然通过社交媒体帖子所谈论的内容实际上是我们这个时代两位最著名的首席执行官之间的笼子里的争斗。</p><p>马斯克和扎克伯格在 6 月份的一次社交媒体交流中出现了两人之间发生争执的可能性，这就像罗伯特·德尼罗饰演的疯狂出租车司机特拉维斯·比克尔在镜子里与自己对话：“你在和我说话吗？”在扎克伯格先生建议他的公司<a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/META">Meta</a>可能会为马斯克先生的社交媒体公司 Twitter（后来更名为 X）创建一个竞争对手后，马斯克先生发帖称：“如果他愿意<span>的</span>话，我愿意参加一场笼子比赛。 ”在礼节消失之前，首席执行官可能会对此做出十种回应。相反，扎克伯格在他的 Instagram 网络上发布了“发送位置给我”的信息。</p><p>这两位巨头之间争夺社交媒体对话空间的竞争是富有成效的娱乐。看到马斯克在 Twitter 上遇到的麻烦，扎克伯格推出了 Threads，随后马斯克反击，将 Twitter 打造成 X。但这两位亿万富翁似乎手上的时间太多了，不得不用一些时间来填补。冒险走出罗马斗兽场。如果发生的话，笼斗将由与 Meta 合作的终极格斗锦标赛负责人达纳·怀特 (Dana White) 制作。</p><p>此后几周，我们获悉身高 5 英尺 7 英寸、体重 155 磅的扎克伯格先生已成为巴西柔术蓝带。马斯克身高 6 英尺 2 英寸，体重不确定，他声称自己对锻炼没什么兴趣，但在 X 上发帖称，他接受过“无规则街头斗殴”训练。他的前女友、加拿大歌手格莱姆斯表示，马斯克先生“非常坚强”。她还说：“我宁愿这件事没有发生。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多仙境</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-hunter-and-the-rule-of-law-wagner-mutiny-plea-deal-5ced1f57?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">唐纳德·特朗普、亨特·拜登与法治</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 2 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-fbi-loses-the-public-opinion-la-nyc-trust-crime-order-wray-7166e7d8?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">FBI 失去公众关注</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 19 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/-migrant-biden-illegal-undocumented-alien-immigrant-border-wall-desantis-trump-2024-db160555?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">一场破坏性巨大的移民混乱</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 12 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>人们可能会嗤之以鼻，认为这场战斗永远不会发生。我们中的一些人认为特朗普-拜登不会发生，但它已经开始看起来不可避免。如今，无论我们喝什么美国文化之水，我们都可能会看到马斯克和扎克伯格在笼子里试图互相殴打，迫使对方屈服。</p><p>无论人们对安德鲁·卡内基或约翰·D·洛克菲勒等很久以前的美国“强盗大亨”有何看法，</p>他们的钢铁和石油工业是当时的科技巨头，很难想象他们会屈服于笼斗。今天，这是可以想象的最简单的事情。<p></p><p>父母们花费无数的时间寻找让孩子远离社交媒体屏幕的方法，因为他们不想让孩子变成白痴。但事实证明，经营这些公司的人都是白痴。</p><p>扎克伯格花了几个小时在国会作证，证明他是一个严肃的人，他的公司不会对美国年轻人的心理形成构成威胁。然而，扎克伯格和马斯克愿意利用他们在美国商界取得的地位，将自己变成点击诱饵。就连马斯克的母亲梅耶也在推特上表示，“不要鼓励这场婚姻！”但在社交媒体时代，谁愿意听妈妈的话呢？ “妈妈，你为什么不让我看马克·扎克伯格殴打埃隆·马斯克？”</p><p> UFC 的怀特先生表示“这将是格斗运动史上规模最大的一场比赛。”这些天的记忆很短暂。这不会是穆罕默德·阿里和乔·弗雷泽在马尼拉的惊心动魄。它甚至不会上升到比利·简·金和鲍比·里格斯之间的性别之战网球比赛。</p>假设他们没有假装打斗，那么这将是一场尴尬的表演，两个穿着短裤的成年男子在地板上打滚，互相抓对方的肉。优雅。<p></p><p>这两个人所取得的成就通常足以填满几辈子，但他们正在证明当今美国生活的最终目标是让自己成为公众的奇观。马斯克、扎克伯格、特朗普、拜登——美国的低级化即将完成。</p><p><em>写信给 henninger@wsj.com。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-musk-vs-zuck-cage-fight-tech-business-media-ceo-fight-ufc-meta-facebook-twitter-x-11853966</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-musk-vs-zuck-cage-fight-tech-business-media-ceo-fight-ufc-meta-facebook-twitter-x-11853966<author><![CDATA[Daniel Henninger]]></author><category>斗争</category><category>笼斗</category><category>推特</category><category>元</category><category>Facebook</category><category> CEO</category><category>终极格斗冠军赛</category><category>出租车司机</category><category>格斗运动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>马克·扎克伯格</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Perfection Trap’ Review: The Enemy of the Good]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>完美主义似乎是我们这个时代的决定性特征。它并不总是受到如此高度的重视。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590130023263216024"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832863?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿拉米库存照片</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590130023263216024"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">比尔·希维</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 9 日下午 5:54 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-perfection-trap-review-the-enemy-of-the-good-82f4fd43"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>在每次工作面试中，都会有一个时刻，申请人会被要求说出他或她最大的弱点。 “好吧，我不得不说这是我的完美主义”，这是一个聪明的答案，这是一个非常缺乏谦逊的谦虚的自夸。如今，正如托马斯·柯兰（Thomas Curran）在《完美陷阱：拥抱足够好的力量》中所写的那样，这种“弱点”是一种优势。它向未来的雇主保证你对最高标准的承诺，“以不懈的努力、无数的个人牺牲和大量的自我施加压力来计算”。</p><p>完美主义并不总是受到如此高度的重视。它曾经是恐怖的东西。纳撒尼尔·霍桑 (Nathaniel Hawthorne) 于 1843 年创作的警世故事《胎记》讲述了一位科学家对他美丽妻子的唯一缺陷——胎记非常着迷的故事。她将他的厌恶内化，并希望“不惜一切代价”消除这一缺陷。科学家最终配制出了一种治疗方法，他的妻子吞下了它。好吧，除非它会杀了她。课程？完美是一种疯狂，最好避免。</p><p>伦敦经济学院心理学副教授柯兰写道，完美主义“似乎是我们这个时代的决定性特征”。我们日复一日的工作生活充满了这样的观念：“如果你偷懒、放慢速度，或者更糟糕的是，花点时间简单地思考所有无情的磨砺到底是为了什么，那么你就会被淘汰。”被留下来。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/2afcee72-ced3-4242-8443-c43974c673a1.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>我本以为《完美陷阱》会用可预见的正念大杂烩，再加上一点认知行为疗法，也许还加入了一款手机应用程序，来攻击完美主义者（作者自己也算作完美主义者）的弄巧成拙的行为。 Instead, Mr. Curran has produced a manifesto damning our economic system for creating and maintaining a warped set of values that drive perfectionism, values we have internalized without examination. There&#39;s no easy fix, he warns. The task calls for the kind of deep introspection that is both hard and unpopular; we must confront “our most basic assumptions about what&#39;s &#39;great&#39; and &#39;good&#39; in modern society.”</p><p> The case of Lance Armstrong exemplifies the dynamic. The cyclist admitted to doping his way to seven Tour de France victories, but wasn&#39;t sorry for it—it was simply, in his mind, leveling the playing field. “The culture was what it was,” he told Oprah Winfrey. “We were all grown men, we all made our choices.” But step back for a moment, Mr.Curran tells us, and see how Mr. Armstrong is attempting to normalize irrational and shocking behavior. The arms race that he willingly took part in risked every cyclist&#39;s health but didn&#39;t make any single rider more likely to succeed. It paid off for Mr. Armstrong, but not everyone was so lucky, costing some cyclists their health, others their lives.</p><p> “The same destructive arms race is playing out in wider culture right now,” Mr. Curran writes. We subjugate our own well-being to that of the economy, which “needs to grow far more than we need to feel content. Perfectionism is just the collateral damage.” Mr. Curran is explicit. To him, healthy perfectionism—a hedge used by those of us seeking to exclude ourselves from his critique—is an oxymoron.</p><p> Our economy rests on some shaky assumptions. The basic idea, the author tells us, is that an ever-increasing supply of goods and services drives economic growth. More supply means more demand. More demand means more profits. More profits means more jobs. The whirligig must keep spinning.</p><p> Advertising and social media stoke demand by reminding us at every opportunity how lacking we are. The cure is to buy more stuff—new cars, bigger houses, better gadgets, trendier clothes, more expensive cosmetics. I&#39;ve always had a vague sense of these forces, but I&#39;ve never seen this theory laid out so succinctly. As the author writes, “once you see the deficit model by which advertising works, you can&#39;t then unsee it.”</p><p> The lifeblood of social media and advertising is unhappiness. Every day, some two billion of us—a quarter of the earth&#39;s population—log in to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a></p> or Instagram and measure the ways our lives are lacking compared to the photoshopped images of impossibly well-turned-out people living their fabulous lives. “Isn&#39;t this what Instagram is mostly about?” an Instagram employee asked rhetorically in a leaked memo. “The (very photogenic) life of the top 0.1%?” It is. And children pay an especially high price when they feel like they&#39;re falling short. “We make body image issues worse for one in three teen girls,” according to a slide from a leaked Facebook presentation.<p></p><p> Even more disturbing was a leaked chart indicating that 6% of teens in the US and 13% of teens in Britain said “spending time on Instagram was one reason why they felt like they wanted to kill themselves.” The company has no incentive to remedy this. “Facebook (now Meta),” which owns Instagram, “has increased its advertising revenues exponentially since 2009, to almost $115 billion today,” Mr. Curran reminds us. It didn&#39;t do that by telling us we&#39;re fine the way we are. “Their algorithms can even pinpoint moments when young people &#39;need a confidence boost.&#39; ”</p><p> “The Perfection Trap” is a strange and imperfect book. It&#39;s not every day that someone in his early 30s who has worked as a sports psychologist takes on the entire global economy. The charts in it are abysmal, like PowerPoint slides that escaped an institutional bureaucracy. The author&#39;s injunction to accept yourself in all your unique and imperfect glory is too pat. Perfectionism is too deeplyembodied in our lives. And apart from political action, he offers no clear path forward. But maybe those things aren&#39;t his job. As an explanation of how the destructive illusion of perfectionism arises and as a critique of the economy that creates it, this is an important book. One day, Mr. Curran hopes, we may rediscover the truth of the old Italian saying: “Enough is plenty.”</p><p> <em>Mr. Heavey is a writer in Bethesda, Md.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:54:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-perfection-trap-review-the-enemy-of-the-good-82f4fd43</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-perfection-trap-review-the-enemy-of-the-good-82f4fd43<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>General Labor Issues</category><category> Job Search</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>Thomas Curran</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>general news</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>general labor issues</category><category>求职</category><category>内容类型</category><category>factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Songs of the Horizon: David Smith, Music, and Dance’ Review: Rhythms of Abstraction]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The Hyde Collection presents the first museum exhibition to explore the artist&#39;s interest in, and responses to, the performing arts <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080313114498820"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832521?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Cello Player&#39; (1946) by David Smith</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Estate of David Smith / VAGA, ARS, NY </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12108107398966324280204590080313114498820"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Karen Wilkin</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 9, 2023 5:52 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/songs-of-the-horizon-david-smith-music-and-dance-review-hyde-collection-sculpture-746c9be8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> In the spring of 1940, the sculptor David Smith and his wife, the artist Dorothy Dehner, moved permanently to the former fox farm in Bolton Landing, NY, that they had acquired as a summer home in 1929. Previously part of New York City&#39;s small community of vanguard artists, they now lived above Lake George where, as summer residents, they had formed a circle of friends that included artists, art enthusiasts and the curators of the Hyde Collection in nearby Glens Falls, as well as members of the Skidmore College art faculty in Saratoga Springs. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Songs of the Horizon: David Smith, Music, and Dance</strong></p><p> <em>The Hyde Collection, through Sept. 17</em></p></div></div><p> Smith spent most of 1942 and 1943 in Schenectady, welding armor plate onto locomotives and waiting apprehensively to be drafted. Rejected by the Army in 1944—sinus problems—he returned to intense sculpture-making at Bolton Landing and a lively postwar cultural life. An acclaimed cellist who lived in the area and a visiting distinguished harpsichordist gave concerts. There was a chamber music group. The modern dancer Franziska Boas held classes there.</p><p> Smith had some earlier knowledge of modern dance through Dehner&#39;s study of the discipline and had seen Martha Graham perform in New York. His notebooks contain pages of drawings of musical instruments, composers&#39; names, and a note about Aaron Copland&#39;s book “What to Listen for in Music.” At Bolton Landing, his knowledge of dance and music was enhanced by watching Boas&#39;s classes and by a close friendship with a young neighbor, a Yale-educated musician. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="558" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832515?width=700&amp;height=558" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Untitled (Piat)&#39; (1946) by David Smith</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Estate of David Smith / VAGA, ARS, NY</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Now, as part of the Hyde Collection&#39;s 60th anniversary celebrations, the exhibition “Songs of the Horizon: David Smith, Music, and Dance” focuses on Smith&#39;s responses to these opportunities. Organized by Jennifer Field, executive director of the Estate of David Smith, the exhibition assembles 31 two- and three-dimensional works from private and public collections—a sampling of Smith&#39;s sculptures and drawings related to the theme, mainly from the 1940s, with some works by Dehner.</p><p> It&#39;s a very narrow slice of this brilliant artist&#39;s achievement, with terrific works and problematic ones. The elegantly installed show is informative, with some rarely seen inclusions. It confirms Smith&#39;s connection to the region and reminds us that while he thought of himself as a sculptor, he never stopped drawing or painting. But many included works attempt to embody free association in literal, Surrealist-inflected ways, not always convincingly. A 1944 painting and some 1946 drawings conflate a cello, an insect and a human body without real transformation. Happily, the steel sculpture “Cello Player” (1946), a generous, inventive, open cage of rods and angled planes alluding only obliquely to the nominal subject, is infinitely more compelling.</p><p> In 1946, Smith fused a harpsichord and performer in works on paper that verge on the grotesque (but have splendid color). He pursued the idea in both two and three dimensions in multiple versions of “Terpsichore and Euterpe,” a blocky abstracted piano awkwardly bracketed by a blocky abstracted pianist and a blocky abstracted dancer. He evidently was pleased with the 1947 bronze iteration of the motif, with a green patina, since he allowed a close friend, a dedicated collector, to acquire it, but a more ambiguous “Euterpe and Terpsichore” (1946), in burnished bronze, succeeds better. That ambiguity is decisive in “Egyptian Landscape” (1951); its swelling bronze forms, cradled by painted steel “drawing,” provoke infinite associations—including, if we choose, with dance or music—without limiting them to preconceptions. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832516?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Euterpe and Terpsichore&#39; (1946) by David Smith</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Estate of David Smith / VAGA, ARS, NY</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The best of the dance sculptures are specific without seeming literal. The intimate bronze “At the Bar” (1941)—it should be “barre”—turns the downward plunge of an arabesque penché into taut calligraphy. The aggressively frontal “Boaz Dancing School” (1945) seems straightforward, with its tipped floor plane, a small dancer at the back, a larger one in the middle and an overscaled seated figure in the foreground, but proves spatially complex. The relative sizes of the trio exaggerate the sense of distance, but logic is challenged by the figure farthest away being the most naturalistic, while the closest is the most abstract. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="691" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832519?width=700&amp;height=691" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Boaz Dancing School&#39; (1945) by David Smith</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: The Estate of David Smith / VAGA, ARS, NY</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Dehner is represented by early paintings of the farm and two works from the Hyde&#39;s collection, a weblike colored etching and a pierced bronze “screen,” both made after she and Smith separated. They bear witness to her accomplishment and the aesthetic sophistication that led Smith to write “I owe my direction to you.”</p><p> At the Hyde, Smith&#39;s tall, slender sculptures “Sentinel V” (1959), stainless steel, and “Lunar Arcs on One Leg” (1956-62), steel painted yellow, suggest the persistence of ideas stated in the 1940s, but a broader view of the mature Smith is offered by five leggy, personable sculptures at the Empire State Plaza, in Albany—or would be, if they were not lined up against the light in a glass-walled corner of an office tower there. Made in 1963 at Bolton Landing with obsolete tools and other elements from the abandoned Italian steel factory where he built the works memorably installed in the Roman amphitheater of Spoleto, for the 1962 Festival of the Two Worlds, the delicately poised, resolutely abstract constructions are as dancer-like as anything in Glens Falls.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。 Wilkin is an independent curator and critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/songs-of-the-horizon-david-smith-music-and-dance-review-hyde-collection-sculpture-746c9be8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/songs-of-the-horizon-david-smith-music-and-dance-review-hyde-collection-sculpture-746c9be8<category>艺术评论</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Dance/Ballet</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>艺术</category><category>政治的</category><category>general news</category><category>舞蹈</category><category>芭蕾舞</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Playing for the Man at the Door’ Review: Mack McCormick’s Musical Discoveries]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Smithsonian Folkways presents a boxed set of decades of previously unreleased field recordings from the musicologist&#39;s archive, featuring Texas musicians like Mance Lipscomb and &#39;Hop&#39; Wilson <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128521020006684"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="1290" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831016?width=860&amp;height=1290" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mack McCormick</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Redferns </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128521020006684"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Barry Mazor</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 9, 2023 5:49 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/playing-for-the-man-at-the-door-review-mack-mccormicks-musical-discoveries-cc304817"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> People who know the name Mack McCormick have most often heard about him as the relentless, secretive researcher who, through the 1970s, pursued the life story of the esteemed but biographically mysterious Mississippi bluesman Robert Johnson. He found documents, photos and the testimony of Johnson&#39;s family and friends, then kept what he&#39;d written about it under wraps for so long that the blues world wondered if they&#39;d ever see it. Suffering from both poverty and a variety of mental illnesses, McCormick (1930-2015) became so obsessive about keeping his copious findings private that he added red-herring misinformation to his writings to throw off anyone who might encounter and try to exploit them.</p><p> His riveting prose on his search for Johnson, carefully edited, was released earlier this year when the Smithsonian published a version of his book “Biography of a Phantom.” But that was hardly McCormick&#39;s only area of obsessive pursuit and artifact hoarding. A fascinating collection of 66 of the field recordings he captured in Texas and nearby locations has just been released as a 3-CD boxed set, “Playing for the Man at the Door: Field Recordings From the Collection of Mack McCormick 1958-1971,” which includes a lavish and informative 128-page book spelling out who the largely unknown artists he found were and McCormick&#39;s recording adventures that led to the tracks. (A 6-LP version will follow next month.) The set reveals much about what the obsessive self-made folklorist was hunting for, and lets loose hours of exciting, previously unheard music.</p><p> His hundreds of field recordings of a wide variety of vernacular roots music, along with massive collections of everything from regional recipes to location photos, were stored in an untapped archive he called “the Monster.” As his daughter, Susannah Nix, reveals in the set&#39;s book, he never even went back and listened to what he&#39;d collected, let alone shared it. Some of it is now being shared—and it&#39;s as different from the conventional as he was.</p><p> More traditional folklorists habitually ignored or even suppressed music they came across that wasn&#39;t in keeping with their special genre interest, artists who weren&#39;t sufficiently “isolated” from popular culture, and performances of songs that had been commercially available, however compelling. McCormick proves more accepting and inclusive, having recorded whatever he found lively and fresh—much to the benefit of this collection&#39;s listeners.</p><p> It explores well beyond the confines of rural Texas blues, and the folk and roots-rock scenes&#39; predilection for single, sorrowful men with guitars. There&#39;s Creole zydeco pioneer Dudley Alexander pumping through a whirling bilingual “St. James Infirmary” in a Houston club; a fellow who called himself “Bongo Joe” hammering Caribbean-style steel drums near the docks in Galveston while shouting hilarious slogans nominating himself for president; and black cowboy James Tisdom, who provides a danceable solo version of “Salty Dog Rag,” apparently picked up and twisted from the hit record by country star Red Foley. “Hop” Wilson cries the BB King-popularized “3 O&#39;Clock Blues” while playing stinging, country-like lap steel guitar—a true rarity. The variety continues with medicine-show pitches and even faster-talking auctioneers&#39; shouts.</p><p> The outright blues recordings include a welcome, relatively rare extension from guitar into piano blues. A performer known as “The Grey Ghost” for popping in and out of towns as if by magic plays remarkably lowdown piano while singing “One Room Country Shack,” and EB Busby plays “Swanee River Boogie” in the classic, hard-pounding boogie-woogie style.</p><p> Likely to get particular attention in the set are McCormick&#39;s revelatory early catches of three blues men who became widely recognized names in the years that followed. Sharecropper-turned-songster Mance Lipscomb is heard doing his brave talking and singing report on a notoriously cruel plantation boss of the previous era, “ Tom Moore&#39;s Farm”; “Lightnin&#39;” Hopkins is found as he&#39;s evolving his material from the R&amp;B he&#39;d recorded earlier to the live, improvised story songs that would make him a model for countless singer-songwriters, on “World&#39;s in a Tangle.” (“You can read between the words,” he suggests.) Both were soon recording with McCormick&#39;s buddy Chris Strachwitz on his new Arhoolie label. A third, always stunning singer, CeDell Davis, is heard younger and more powerful on “Darlin&#39; (You Know I Love You),” 30 years before he became a 1990s blues star on Fat Possum records.</p><p> The great majority of the artists assembled here are black men, and the book—in commentary by producers Jeff Place and John W. Troutman, scholar-songster Dom Flemons, and the Smithsonian&#39;s Mark Puryear —does a good job describing and extrapolating on male African-American musicians&#39; lives in the region at the time. But McCormick recorded virtually no women, so they are regrettably and quite noticeably absent here.</p><p> That may well be another artifact of his personal demons. Yet, despite his troubles, when this “man at the door” came calling, he charmed a broad range of gifted, utterly unsung music-makers into performing. Now we get to hear what they played for McCormick—and to learn more about who he was.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Mazor reviews country and roots music for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/playing-for-the-man-at-the-door-review-mack-mccormicks-musical-discoveries-cc304817</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/playing-for-the-man-at-the-door-review-mack-mccormicks-musical-discoveries-cc304817<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>general news</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Mark Morris Dance Group Review: Radiant Renewal in New York]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The troupe&#39;s current two-week run is its first season at the Joyce Theater and highlights its triumphant return to the stage after the Covid-19 pandemic. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590140123025311674"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832982?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mark Morris Dance Group performing &#39;Grand Duo&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Danica Paulos </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590140123025311674"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Robert Greskovic</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 9, 2023 5:47 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-morris-dance-group-review-radiant-renewal-in-new-york-2f81a054"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><em>纽约</em></p><p>The Mark Morris Dance Group&#39;s two-week season at the Joyce Theater opened on Aug. 1 with Program A, a beautifully paced, two-part bill of four dances dating from 1993 to 2017. The run continues through Saturday with Program B, another two-part arrangement of four works. Half of B&#39;s dances are new to New York—a world premiere and a stage debut following a 2021 livestreamed performance. The oldest work in the second program is from 1980, the year Mr. Morris formed his dance group in the city. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Mark Morris Dance Group</strong></p><p><strong></strong> <em>Joyce Theater, through Aug. 12</em></p></div></div><p> The Joyce season, a first for the troupe, represents a return to some normality after the Covid-19 pandemic brought a halt to the Morris company&#39;s previously busy touring schedule. “It&#39;s just really been tough coming back, and now we&#39;re back,” Mr. Morris recently told the web publication Fjord Review.</p><p> Over his widely acclaimed career as a choreographer, Mr. Morris has been consistently identified as a “music man” to stress the grounding his work finds in that medium. This focus, with rare exceptions, requires music being performed live, and in the Joyce—a converted movie house with no pit, where recordings are the prevailing option—this means finding room for musicians and their instruments.</p><p> Among the charms of “Numerator” (2017)—the five-section dance for six men that opened Program A—was the presence of the MMDG Music Ensemble, arrayed on both sides of the house below the apron of the stage, playing Lou Harrison&#39;s “Varied Trio for Violin, Piano, and Percussion.” Their reverberating tintinnabulations fed Mr. Morris&#39;s evolving display of artfully gestural moves for the dance suite, which grows from a crawling start into sequences of game-like activity, hinting at a life-cycle born of prone postures that move into freestanding, often-times athletic articulations.</p><p> The stirring physicalities and patterns of “Polka,” the jaunty as well as heady final movement of Harrison&#39;s “Grand Duo,” which serves as the title of Mr. Morris&#39;s 1993 dance, closed out Program A thrillingly as its cast of 14 climaxed the four-part dance by conjuring a ferociously driven tribal ritual. Program B opens winningly with “Tempus Perfectum,” set to “Sixteen Waltzes, Op. 39” by Johannes Brahms. The work for two women and two men began life as a 2021 streaming presentation with its cast in face masks.</p><p> Mr. Morris&#39;s dancers romp and breeze through “Tempus Perfectum” with various waltzing moves that pay winking homage to Isadora Duncan, who choreographed Brahms waltzes in the early 20th century. His choreography tweaks the pliant soft edge of Duncanesque waltzes by having his performers pace through their dancing with sometimes proudly flexed feet and sometimes almost punchy accents. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Dance Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pilobolus-review-the-dance-theater-troupes-big-five-oh-69dc2f93?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Pilobolus Review: The Dance-Theater Troupe&#39;s &#39;Big Five-Oh!&#39;</a> <span class="date">2023 年 7 月 20 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/like-water-for-chocolate-review-an-overstuffed-ballet-5c74e2e5?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Like Water for Chocolate&#39; Review: An Overstuffed Ballet</a> <span class="date">June 28, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-york-city-ballet-review-balanchine-and-beyond-d98f57a9?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">New York City Ballet Review: Balanchine and Beyond</a> <span class="date">May 9, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/martha-graham-dance-company-in-its-founders-shadow-781038c7?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">Martha Graham Dance Company: In Its Founder&#39;s Shadow</a> <span class="date">April 26, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> Mr. Morris&#39;s world premiere, “A minor Dance,” to Johann Sebastian Bach&#39;s Partita No. 3 in A minor, BWV 827, brings his catalog of dances to 183. The seven-parter, for three women and three men, presents his dancers in Elizabeth Kurtzman&#39;s softly tailored two-piece costuming, their lower bodies brightly colored and their torsos more neutrally hued. The choreography mixes and meshes the six performers—animated groupings evoke flocks of birds and then give way to slumber-party arrangements before there is a concentration on stage-crossing moves for dancers who strike frieze-like flattened postures more individually than as a bonded group. At least from one viewing, “A minor Dance” feels not so much minor as strung out.</p><p> “All Fours” (2003), which precedes “A minor Dance” here, moves compellingly through Béla Bartók&#39;s String Quartet No. 4, played vibrantly by the Aeolus Quartet clustered on the right side of the auditorium. Mr. Morris&#39;s choreography builds intriguingly through the dramatic framing of Nicole Pearce&#39;s often stark lighting changes as an ensemble of eight black-clad men and women are joined by two featured men ( Dallas McMurray and Billy Smith ) and subsequently two women ( Courtney Lopes and Christina Sahaida</p> ）。<p></p><p> In their softer, ecru-colored costuming designed by Martin Pakledinaz, the two couples of “All Fours” move more freely than their dark-clad fellows. All the while, the insistent drive of Bartók&#39;s quartet impels this display of individuality against group force.</p><p> “Castor and Pollux,” Mr. Morris&#39;s 1980 effort, closes Program B on an inconclusive note. Set to music of the same name by Harry Partch that is the bill&#39;s only taped accompaniment, this eight-dancer excursion is awash in percussion reminiscent of Indonesian gamelan playing; flattened postures and frieze-like moments show us where some of Mr. Morris&#39;s abiding inventions originated. But after a single viewing, “Castor and Pollux” feels rich of pattern rather than theatrically coherent. In the 43 years since the creation of “Castor and Pollux,” Mr. Morris&#39;s dancemaking, as is vividly evident on these programs, has made more indelible marks. They are most welcome again on New York&#39;s dance scene.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Greskovic writes about dance for the Journal.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 09 Aug 2023 21:47:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-morris-dance-group-review-radiant-renewal-in-new-york-2f81a054</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mark-morris-dance-group-review-radiant-renewal-in-new-york-2f81a054<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>Dance/Ballet</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>音乐</category><category>疫情/流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>general news</category><category>呼吸道疾病</category><category>舞蹈</category><category>芭蕾舞</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>音乐</category><category>爆发</category><category>流行病</category><category>新型冠状病毒</category><category>传染性疾病</category><category>内容类型</category><category>factiva filters</category><category> c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item></channel></rss>